The Niddel app for Splunk provides an integration between Splunk and the Niddel
Magnet service. Its objective is to flag suspicious activities and
communications performed by machines on the organization's network which
indicates that they are likely  to be infected with malware and/or compromised.

To achieve that end, it generates regular statistical summaries of communications
originated by machines in your network towards external addresses. These are based on
firewall and web proxy logs indexed in Splunk. The summaries are packaged
and uploaded to the Niddel Magnet back-end for processing using the `niddel2_firewall`
and `niddel2_proxy` saved searches.

The Niddel Magnet engine in the cloud uses groundbreaking machine learning and
data science techniques, cyber threat intelligence indicators from a variety of
sources, and the historical patterns of communications of each organization's
network to determine a very small subset of potentially infected or compromised
machines. This technology is known for generating very accurate results, and is
able to extrapolate from existing threat data to detect novel threats before
other existing security products.

Upon receiving those suspicious communications, organizations' information
security monitoring, digital forensics and/or incident response teams can then
focus on the analysis of the small group of internal machines that originated
them.

A valid Niddel Magnet API key is needed to use this, please e-mail us at
contact@niddel.com if you wish to start a trial. Splunk customers can learn more
at the knowledge base at https://support.niddel.com using their Niddel Magnet
Portal credentials.

The dashboard content relies on the ingestion of Niddel Magnet alerts into Splunk
through our separate add-on available at https://splunkbase.splunk.com/app/3710/.

The app implements three new custom commands:

* `niddelorganizations` lists the organizations accessible on the Niddel Magnet
v2 API with the currently configured API key. It is used to populate drop-down
of organizations on the credentials and log collection setup pages.
Details: https://api.niddel.com/v2#operation--organizations-get

* `niddelsend` is used in app-generated saved searches as the final step that
actually uploads data into the Niddel Magnet cloud back-end. It does this by
using the Niddel v2 API to obtain temporary AWS credentials and then using them
to upload the logs as gzipped files into the organization's S3 bucket. This is
not meant to be used directly in searches unless explicitly requested by the
Niddel support team.

* `niddelparseurl` is used in app-generated saved searches to help normalize
the event data prior to the upload into the Niddel Magnet cloud back-end.
This is not meant to be used directly in searches unless explicitly requested
by the Niddel support team.

This app includes the following 3rd party Python packages under
bin/niddel2_imports:

* botocore 1.8.36 (https://pypi.python.org/pypi/botocore/1.8.36)
* boto3 1.5.2 (https://pypi.python.org/pypi/boto3/1.5.22)
* certifi 2018.01.18 (https://pypi.python.org/pypi/certifi/2018.01.18)
* chardet 3.0.4 (https://pypi.python.org/pypi/chardet/3.0.4)
* python-dateutil 2.6.1 (https://pypi.python.org/pypi/python-dateutil/2.6.1)
* decorator 4.1.2 (https://pypi.python.org/pypi/decorator/4.1.2)
     - included as the single file bin/niddel2_imports/validators/decorator.py
* futures 3.2.0 (https://pypi.python.org/pypi/futures/3.2.0)
* idna 2.6 (https://pypi.python.org/pypi/idna/2.6)
* ipaddress 1.0.18 (https://pypi.python.org/pypi/ipaddress/1.0.18)
* iso8601 0.1.12 (https://pypi.python.org/pypi/iso8601/0.1.12)
* jmespath 0.9.3 (https://pypi.python.org/pypi/jmespath/0.9.3)
* Niddel Magnet v2 API SDK 1.5.4 (https://github.com/Niddel/magnet-api2-sdk-python)
* python-dateutil 2.6.1 (https://pypi.python.org/pypi/python-dateutil/2.6.1)
* requests 2.18.4 (https://pypi.python.org/pypi/requests/2.18.4)
* s3transfer 0.1.12 (https://pypi.python.org/pypi/s3transfer/0.1.12)
* six 1.10.0 (https://pypi.python.org/pypi/six/1.10.0)
* smart_open 1.3.3 (https://pypi.python.org/pypi/smart_open/1.3.3)
     - included class BufferedOutputBase from https://github.com/RaRe-Technologies/smart_open/blob/master/smart_open/s3.py used in bin/NiddelSend.py
* splunklib 1.6.2 (https://pypi.python.org/pypi/splunk-sdk/1.6.2)
* unicodecsv 0.14.1 (https://pypi.python.org/pypi/unicodecsv/0.14.1)
* uritools 2.0.0 (https://pypi.python.org/pypi/uritools/2.0.0)
* urllib3 1.22 (https://pypi.python.org/pypi/urllib3/1.22)
* validators 0.12.0 (https://pypi.python.org/pypi/validators/0.12.0)

This app includes the following 3rd party JavaScript packages:

* text.js 2.0.15 (https://github.com/requirejs/text/tree/2.0.15)
